@startuml
!include ../../style.puml

title Torn Writes and Recovery

actor Application as App
box "OS Layer" #LightBlue
participant "File System" as FS
participant "OS Page Cache\n(4KB pages)" as Cache
end box
box "Storage Layer" #LightGray
participant "Block Layer" as Block
participant "Block Device" as Dev
database "Stable Media" as Media
end box

' [step1 {"name":"Write Intent"}]
== Write Intent ==
App -> FS: write(record[8KB])
FS -> Cache: copy to dirty pages
FS --> App: return success
' [/step1]

' [step2 {"name":"Flush to Disk"}]
== Flush to Disk ==
App -> FS: fsync(fd)
FS -> Cache: select dirty pages
Cache -> Block: submit writes
Block -> Dev: write logical blocks

note over Dev
An 8KB record spans many device blocks.
Persistence may happen a block at a time.
end note
' [/step2]

' [step3 {"name":"Power Loss", "newPage":"true"}]
== Power Loss ==
Dev -> Media: persist only a prefix of blocks
note over Dev,Media #FFEEEE
Only part of the intended record reached stable media.
The tail now contains mixed old and new bytes.
This is a torn write.
end note
' [/step3]

' [step4 {"name":"Recovery"}]
== Recovery ==
App -> FS: restart and recover
FS -> Cache: read WAL tail
Cache -> Dev: verify header, length, checksum
Dev -> Cache: return mixed bytes

note over Cache #FFFFCC
Checksum or length mismatch reveals
that the tail is ambiguous.
end note

Cache -> FS: truncate to last valid record
FS --> App: replay valid records only

note bottom #E6FFE6
**WAL Guardrails**
• Frame each record
• Add checksums
• fsync at commit boundaries
• Truncate ambiguous tails
• Replay idempotently
end note
' [/step4]

@enduml
